#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:6
msgid "Summary"
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:9
msgid ""
"Introduce a move to dual-MIT/Apache2 licensing terms to the Rust RFCs repo, "
"by requiring them for all new contributions, and asking previous "
"contributors to agree on the new license."
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:13
msgid "Disclaimer"
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:16
msgid "This RFC is not authored by a lawyer, so its reasoning may be wrong."
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:18
msgid "Motivation"
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:21
msgid ""
"Currently, the Rust RFCs repo is in a state where no clear open source "
"license is specified."
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:24
msgid ""
"The current legal base of the RFCs repo is the \"License Grant to Other "
"Users\" from the [Github ToS](https://help.github.com/articles/github-terms-"
"of-service/#5-license-grant-to-other-users)`*`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:27
msgid ""
"```\n"
"Any Content you post publicly, including issues, comments, and contributions "
"to other Users' repositories, may be viewed by others. By setting your "
"repositories to be viewed publicly, you agree to allow others to view and "
"\"fork\" your repositories (this means that others may make their own copies "
"of your Content in repositories they control).\n"
"\n"
"If you set your pages and repositories to be viewed publicly, you grant each "
"User of GitHub a nonexclusive, worldwide license to access your Content "
"through the GitHub Service, and to use, display and perform your Content, "
"and to reproduce your Content solely on GitHub as permitted through GitHub's "
"functionality.\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:33
msgid ""
"These terms may be sufficient for display of the rfcs repository on Github, "
"but it limits contributions and use, and even poses a risk."
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:36
msgid ""
"The Github ToS grant only applies towards reproductions through the Github "
"Service. Hypothetically, if the Github Service ceases at some point in the "
"future, without a legal successor offering a replacement service, the RFCs "
"may not be redistributed any more."
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:41
msgid ""
"Second, there are companies which have set up policies that limit their "
"employees to contribute to the RFCs repo in this current state."
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:44
msgid ""
"Third, there is the possibility that Rust may undergo standardisation and "
"produce a normative document describing the language. Possibly, the authors "
"of such a document may want to include text from RFCs."
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:48
msgid ""
"Fourth, the spirit of the Rust project is to be open source, and the current "
"terms don't fulfill any popular open source definition."
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:51
msgid ""
"`*`: The Github ToS is licensed under the [Creative Commons Attribution "
"license](https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/)"
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:55
msgid "Detailed design"
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:58
msgid ""
"After this RFC has been merged, all new RFCs will be required to be dual-"
"licensed under the MIT/Apache2. This includes RFCs currently being "
"[considered for merging](https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/pulls)."
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:62
msgid ""
"`README.md` should include a note that all contributions to the repo should "
"be licensed under the new terms."
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:65
msgid ""
"As the licensing requires consent from the RFC creators, an issue will be "
"created on rust-lang/rfcs with a list of past contributors to the repo, "
"asking every contributor to agree to their contributions to be licensed "
"under those terms."
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:70
msgid ""
"Regarding non-RFC files in this repo, the intention is to get them licensed "
"as well, not just the RFCs themselves. Therefore, contributors should be "
"asked to license _all_ their contributions to this repo, not just to the RFC "
"files, and _all_ new contributions to this repo should be required to be "
"licensed under the new terms."
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:78
msgid "How We Teach This"
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:81
msgid ""
"The issue created should @-mention all Github users who have contributed, "
"generating a notification for each past contributor."
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:84
msgid ""
"Also, after this RFC got merged, all RFCs in the queue will get a comment in "
"their Github PR and be asked to include the copyright section at the top of "
"their RFC file."
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:88
msgid ""
"The note in README.md should inform new PR authors of the terms they put "
"their contribution under."
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:91
msgid "Drawbacks"
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:94
msgid ""
"This is additional churn and pings a bunch of people, which they may not "
"like."
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:96
msgid "Alternatives"
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:99
msgid ""
"Other licenses more suited for text may have been chosen, like the CC-BY "
"license. However, RFCs regularly include code snippets, which may be used in "
"the rust-lang/rust, and similarly, RFCs may want to include code snippets "
"from rust-lang/rust. It might be the case that the CC-BY license allows such "
"sharing, but it might also mean complications."
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:105
msgid ""
"Also, the [swift-evolution](https://github.com/apple/swift-evolution) "
"repository is put under the Apache license as well."
msgstr ""

#: src/2044-license-rfcs.md:108
msgid ""
"Maybe for something like this, no RFC is needed. However, there exists "
"precedent on non technical RFCs with RFC 1636. Also, this issue has been "
"known for years and no action has been done on this yet. If this RFC gets "
"closed as too trivial or offtopic, and the issue is being acted upon, its "
"author considers it a successful endeavor."
msgstr ""

